Curing is the process of preserving the moisture content and temperature of newly poured concrete until it attains the necessary strength. Curing is crucial for the appropriate development of the characteristics and durability of concrete. After concrete has been poured and cured, it must be maintained wet in order for the chemical processes that occur during hydration to continue. These interactions culminate in the creation of calcium silicate hydrate (CSH), which imparts strength and durability to concrete. If the concrete dries out during this phase, the synthesis of CSH is impeded, and the concrete will not attain the appropriate strength. Several techniques may be used to cure concrete, including ponding, misting, covering it with curing agents or wet burlap, or utilizing a curing membrane. The most typical technique for curing concrete involves applying water to the surface by ponding, misting, or spraying. Curing concrete is important because it guarantees that the concrete attains the necessary strength and durability. Concrete that has been properly cured is less porous to water and other liquids, making it more resistant to freeze-thaw cycles, chemical assault, and wear. In addition, curing prevents concrete from cracking, scaling, and surface flaws. Curing concrete is a crucial procedure that guarantees the concrete attains the appropriate strength and durability and becomes less porous to water and other liquids, hence increasing its resistance to freeze-thaw cycles, chemical assault, and wear. 